 our cuisine, and our nation of immigrant traditions has produced a distinctive and evolving repertoire that is neither hodgepodge nor smorgasbord. Contributors, who come from the diverse worlds of universities, museums, the media, and gastronomy, look at Canada's distinctive foodways from the shared perspective of the current moment. Individual chapters explore food items and choices, from those made by Canada's First Nations and early settlers to those made today. Other contributions describe the ways in which foods enjoyed by early Canadians have found their way back onto Canadian tables in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. Authors emphasize the expressive potential of food practices and food texts; cookbooks are more than books to be read and used in the kitchen, they are also documents that convey valuable social and historical information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCooking, CanadianxHistory. 0aFood habitszCanadaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aBoyd, Shelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickenson, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDraper, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDriver, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFee, Margery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunew, Sneja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenneally, Rhona Richman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemasson, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato